View of the U.S. Capitol
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/easter-egg-roll-capitol.jpg
                    
					Beginning in the early 1800s, Washington, D.C., families gathered on the Capitol grounds on the Monday after Easter to participate in an annual egg roll. The game, in which participants push eggs through grass with spoons, likely derived from centuries-old European customs of rolling eggs down hills after Easter.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Rutherford and Lucy Hayes
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/rutherford-lucy-hayes.jpg
                    
					But in 1876, fed up with mangled lawns and abandoned eggs left to rot, Congress passed a law forbidding the use of Capitol property as a playground. Disappointed children complained to President Rutherford Hayes and his wife, Lucy, who in 1878 invited them to hold the festivities on the White House lawn.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Children Roll Eggs in 1889
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/easter-egg-roll-1889.jpg
                    
					Thanks to President Hayes and his first lady, the 135-year-old tradition of the White House Easter Egg Roll was born. In addition to the egg roll, organizers and participants developed other competitions in those early years, including egg picking, egg ball and egg croquet. (Library of Congress)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Children at the 1923 Egg Roll
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/easter-egg-roll-1923.jpg
                    
					Since its inception, the gathering has taken place almost every year, canceled only due to bad weather and during World War I and World War II. (Whitehouse.gov)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Grace Coolidge at the 1927 Egg Roll
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/easter-egg-roll-raccoon.jpg
                    
					The event allowed local youngsters to interact with members of the first family, including Grace Coolidge, who showed off her pet raccoon at the 1927 White House Easter Egg Roll. (Library of Congress)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Children Jump Rope in 1898
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/egg-roll-jumping-rope.jpg
                    
					Over the years, organizers began to incorporate additional activities, including musical performances, readings by celebrities and fitness demonstrations. (Library of Congress)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Guests Pose With the Easter Bunny in 2002
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/easter-egg-roll-bunny.jpg
                    
					Since the Nixon administration, the appearance of the Easter bunny has been a key part of the festivities. Senior White House staffers often don the heavy costume to play the role. (Mark Wilson/Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					2013 Souvenir Eggs
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/easter-egg-roll-keepsake-eggs.jpg
                    
					In 1981 Ronald and Nancy Reagan introduced keepsake wooden eggs bearing the signatures of actors, politicians and athletes. The mementos have been part of the celebration ever since. (Whitehouse.gov)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Colorful Eggs in a Basket During a Rainy 2005 Egg Roll
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/easter-egg-roll-basket.jpg
                    
					The history of the White House Egg Roll is not without its scandals. As former first lady Laura Bush recounts in her book “Spoken From the Heart,” in 2006 staffers uncovered a ring of elderly volunteers who were secretly pilfering keepsake eggs by stashing them in portable toilets. (Joe Raedle/Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Children Roll Eggs on the South Lawn in 2006
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/easter-egg-roll-2006.jpg
                    
					While the president typically attends the White House Easter Egg Roll, there have been some exceptions. For instance, Lyndon Johnson preferred to spend Easter at his Texas ranch. (Mark Wilson/Getty Images)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					First Family and Visiting Children Roll Eggs in 2009
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/easter-egg-roll-first-family.jpg
                    
					This year, some 35,000 guests will attend Monday’s event. According to reports, this year’s party will include yoga, appearances by NFL players and cooking demonstrations inspired by first lady Michelle Obama’s Let’s Move! campaign. (Win McNamee/Getty Images)
